    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-04-18T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-04-18T20:00:00-05:00" n="370"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d370">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.61331/140: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Tsingtao</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sokobin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tsingtao</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-04-19T09:00:00+08:00"
                            >April 19, 1939—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 20—4:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>81. A representative of the Universal Leaf Tobacco Company has informed the
                    Consulate that he learns the Japanese authorities are indicating opposition to a
                    plan on which the company has been working for some time to utilize the
                    organization of the well known Japanese trading firm Okura and Company for
                    purchase and transportation of 1939 tobacco crop. It has been indicated that the
                    Universal must enter the combine of Japanese firms mentioned in the Embassy’s
                    telegram No. 623 of October 15, 10 a.m., 1938,<note n="39" xml:id="d370fn39">
                        <ref target="frus1938v04#pg_67">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1938, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 67</ref>.</note> and come to some sort
                    of agreement with these firms.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Chungking, Peiping. By mail to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sokobin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
